	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">World Happiness Report</h1>
	
	<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
		<div id="contentSub"></div>
		
		
		<div id="jump-to-nav"></div>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
		<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#p-search">Jump to search</a>
		<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><p>The <b>World Happiness Report</b> is an annual publication of the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> Sustainable Development Solutions Network. It contains articles, and rankings of national <a href="/wiki/Happiness" title="Happiness">happiness</a> based on respondent ratings of their own lives,<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> which the report also correlates with various life factors.<sup id="cite_ref-auto_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> As of March 2020, <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> was ranked the happiest country in the world three times in a row.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT-20180314_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-20180314-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-USN-20180314_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USN-20180314-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The Editors of the report are <a href="/wiki/John_F._Helliwell" title="John F. Helliwell">John F. Helliwell</a>, <a href="/wiki/Richard_Layard" class="mw-redirect" title="Richard Layard">Richard Layard</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jeffrey_D._Sachs" class="mw-redirect" title="Jeffrey D. Sachs">Jeffrey D. Sachs</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Jan-Emmanuel_De_Neve" title="Jan-Emmanuel De Neve">Jan-Emmanuel De Neve</a>. Associate Editors are Lara B. Aknin, Shun Wang, and Haifang Huang.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In July 2011, the <a href="/wiki/UN_General_Assembly" class="mw-redirect" title="UN General Assembly">UN General Assembly</a> adopted resolution 65/309 <i>Happiness: Towards a Holistic Definition of Developmen</i>t<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> inviting member countries to measure the happiness of their people and to use the data to help guide public policy. On April 2, 2012, this was followed by the first UN High Level Meeting called <i>Wellbeing and Happiness: Defining a New Economic Paradigm</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> which was chaired by UN Secretary General <a href="/wiki/Ban_Ki-moon" title="Ban Ki-moon">Ban Ki-moon</a> and Prime Minister <a href="/wiki/Jigme_Thinley" title="Jigme Thinley">Jigme Thinley</a> of <a href="/wiki/Bhutan" title="Bhutan">Bhutan</a>, a nation that adopted <a href="/wiki/Gross_national_happiness" class="mw-redirect" title="Gross national happiness">gross national happiness</a> instead of <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">gross domestic product</a> as their main development indicator.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The first World Happiness Report was released on April 1, 2012 as a foundational text for the UN <i>High Level Meeting: Well-being and Happiness: Defining a New Economic Paradigm</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> drawing international attention.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> The report outlined the state of world happiness, causes of happiness and misery, and policy implications highlighted by case studies. In 2013, the second World Happiness Report was issued, and since then has been issued on an annual basis with the exception of 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> The report primarily uses data from the <a href="/wiki/Gallup_(company)#Gallup_World_Poll" title="Gallup (company)">Gallup World Poll</a>. Each annual report is available to the public to download on the World Happiness Report website.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Methods_and_philosophy">Methods and philosophy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Methods and philosophy">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The rankings of national <a href="/wiki/Happiness" title="Happiness">happiness</a> are based on a <a href="/wiki/Happiness#Measurement" title="Happiness">Cantril ladder</a> survey. Nationally representative samples of respondents are asked to think of a ladder, with the best possible life for them being a 10, and the worst possible life being a 0. They are then asked to rate their own current lives on that 0 to 10 scale.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> The report correlates the results with various life factors.<sup id="cite_ref-auto_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the reports, experts in fields including <a href="/wiki/Economics" title="Economics">economics</a>, <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Survey_methodology" title="Survey methodology">survey</a> analysis, and <a href="/wiki/Official_statistics" title="Official statistics">national statistics</a>, describe how measurements of <a href="/wiki/Well-being" title="Well-being">well-being</a> can be used effectively to assess the progress of nations, and other topics. Each report is organized by chapters that delve deeper into issues relating to <a href="/wiki/Happiness#Definitions" title="Happiness">happiness</a>, including mental illness, the objective benefits of happiness, the importance of ethics, policy implications, and links with the <a href="/wiki/OECD" title="OECD">Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development'</a>s (OECD) approach to measuring <a href="/wiki/Subjective_well-being" title="Subjective well-being">subjective well-being</a> and other international and national efforts.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Annual_report_topics">Annual report topics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Annual report topics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>World Happiness Reports were issued in 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016 (an update), 2017, 2018, 2019, and 2020. In addition to ranking countries happiness and well-being levels, each report has contributing authors and most focus on a subject. The data used to rank countries in each report is drawn from the Gallup World Poll,<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> as well as other sources such as the <a href="/wiki/World_Values_Survey" title="World Values Survey">World Values Survey</a>, in some of the reports. The Gallup World Poll questionnaire<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> measures 14 areas within its core questions: (1) business &amp; economic, (2) citizen engagement, (3) communications &amp; technology, (4) diversity (social issues), (5) education &amp; families, (6) emotions (well-being), (7) environment &amp; energy, (8) food &amp; shelter, (9) government and politics, (10) law &amp; order (safety), (11) health, (12) religion &amp; ethics, (13) transportation, and (14) work.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2019_World_Happiness_Report">2019 World Happiness Report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: 2019 World Happiness Report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The 2018 iteration was released on 20 March and focused on the relation between happiness and migration. According to the 2019 Happiness Report, <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> is the happiest country in the world,<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> with <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iceland" title="Iceland">Iceland</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">The Netherlands</a> holding the next top positions. The World Happiness Report 2018 ranks 156 countries by their happiness levels, and 117 countries by the happiness of their immigrants. The main focus of this year's report, in addition to its usual ranking of the levels and changes in happiness around the world, is on migration within and between countries. The overall rankings of country happiness are based on the pooled results from Gallup World Poll surveys from 2015–2017, and show both change and stability. Four countries have held the top spot in the last four reports: Denmark, Switzerland, Norway and now Finland. All the top countries tend to have high values for all six of the key variables that have been found to support well-being: income, healthy life expectancy, social support, freedom, trust and generosity. Among the top countries, differences are small enough that year-to-year changes in the rankings are to be expected.
</p><p>The analysis of happiness changes from 2008–2015 shows <a href="/wiki/Togo" title="Togo">Togo</a> as the biggest gainer, moving up 17 places in the overall rankings from 2015. The biggest loser is <a href="/wiki/Venezuela" title="Venezuela">Venezuela</a>, down 2.2 points. Five of the report's seven chapters deal primarily with migration, as summarized in Chapter 1. For both domestic and international migrants, the report studies the happiness of those migrants and their host communities, and also of those in the countryside or in the country of origin. The results are generally positive. Perhaps the most striking finding of the whole report is that a ranking of countries according to the happiness of their immigrant populations is almost exactly the same as for the rest of the population. The immigrant happiness rankings are based on the full span of Gallup data from 2005 to 2017, sufficient to have 117 countries with more than 100 immigrant respondents. The ten happiest countries in the overall rankings also make up ten of the top eleven spots in the ranking of immigrant happiness. Finland is at the top of both rankings in this report, with the happiest immigrants, and the happiest population in general. While convergence to local happiness levels is quite rapid, it is not complete, as there is a ‘footprint' effect based on the happiness in each source country. This effect ranges from 10% to 25%. This footprint effect explains why immigrant happiness is less than that of the locals in the happiest countries, while being greater in the least happy countries.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2016_World_Happiness_Report">2016 World Happiness Report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: 2016 World Happiness Report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<tbody><tr>
<th style="background: #F0F2F5; font-size:87%; padding:0.2em 0.3em; text-align:center;"><div style="display:inline;font-size:115%">Descriptions</div>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td style="border: solid 1px Silver; padding: 0.6em; background: White;">
<p>The 2016 World Happiness Report -Rome Addition was issued in two parts as an update. Part one had four chapters: (1) <i>Setting the Stage,</i> (2) <i>The Distribution of World Happiness</i>, (3) <i>Promoting Secular Ethics</i>, and (4) <i>Happiness and Sustainable Development: Concepts and Evidence</i>. Part two has six chapters: (1) <i>Inside the Life Satisfaction Blackbox</i>, (2) <i>Human Flourishing, the Common Good, and Catholic Social Teaching</i>, (3) <i>The Challenges of Public Happiness: An Historical-Methodological Reconstruction</i>, (4) <i>The Geography of Parenthood and Well-Being: Do Children Make Us Happy, Where and Why?</i>, and (5) <i>Multidimensional Well-Being in Contemporary Europe: An Analysis of the Use of a Self-Organizing Map Applied to Share Data</i>.
</p><p>Chapter 1, <i>Setting the Stage</i> is written by John F. Helliwell, Richard Layard, and Jeffrey Sachs. This chapter briefly surveys the happiness movement ("Increasingly, happiness is considered to be the proper measure of social progress and the goal of public policy.") gives an overview of the 2016 reports and synopsis of both parts of the 2016 Update Rome Addition.
</p><p>Chapter 2, <i>The Distribution of World Happiness</i> is written by John F. Helliwell, Hailing Huang, and Shun Wang. This chapter reports happiness levels of countries and proposes the use of inequalities of happiness among individuals as a better measure for inequality than <a href="/wiki/Income_inequality_in_the_United_States" title="Income inequality in the United States">income inequality</a>, and that all people in a population fare better in terms of happiness when there is less inequality in happiness in their region. It includes data from the <a href="/wiki/World_Health_Organization" title="World Health Organization">World Health Organization</a> and <a href="/wiki/World_Development_Indicators" title="World Development Indicators">World Development Indicators</a>, as well as <a href="/wiki/Gallup_(company)" title="Gallup (company)">Gallup</a> World Poll. It debunks the notion that people rapidly adapt to changes in life circumstances and quickly return to an initial life satisfaction <a href="/wiki/Baseline_Study" title="Baseline Study">baseline</a>, finding instead that changes in life circumstances such as <a href="/wiki/Public_policy" title="Public policy">government policies</a>, major life events (<a href="/wiki/Unemployment" title="Unemployment">unemployment</a>, major <a href="/wiki/Disability" title="Disability">disability</a>) and <a href="/wiki/Immigration" title="Immigration">immigration</a> change people's baseline life satisfaction levels. This chapter also addresses the measure for affect (feelings), finding that positive affect (happiness, laughter, enjoyment) has much "large and highly significant impact" on life satisfaction than negative affect (worry, sadness, anger). The chapter also examines differences in happiness levels explained by the factors of (1) social support, (2) income, (3) healthy life, (4) trust in government and business, (5) perceived freedom to make life decisions and (6) generosity.
</p><p>Chapter 3, <i>Promoting Secular Ethics</i> is written by Richard Layard, This chapter argues for a revival of an ethical life and world, harkening to times when <a href="/wiki/Religious_organization" title="Religious organization">religious organizations</a> were a dominant force. It calls on secular non-profit organizations to promote "ethical living in a way that provides inspiration, uplift, joy and mutual respect", and gives examples of implementation by a non-profit founded by Richard Layard,<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> the chapter author, Action for Happiness, which offers online information from <a href="/wiki/Positive_psychology" title="Positive psychology">positive psychology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhist teachings</a>.
</p><p>Chapter 4, <i>Happiness and Sustainable Development: Concepts and Evidence</i> is written by Jeffrey Sachs. This chapter identifies ways that <a href="/wiki/Sustainable_development" title="Sustainable development">sustainable development</a> indicators (economic, social and environmental factors) can be used to explain <a href="/wiki/Statistics" title="Statistics">variations</a> in happiness. It concludes with a report about an appeal to include subjective well-being indicators into the <a href="/wiki/Sustainable_Development_Goals" title="Sustainable Development Goals">UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs)</a>.
</p><p>Part Two <i>2016 Special Rome Edition</i> was edited by Jeffrey Sacks, Leonardo Becchetti and Anthony Arnett.
</p><p>Chapter 1, <i>Inside the Life Satisfaction Blackbox</i> is written by Leonardo Becchetti, Luisa Carrado,<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> and Paolo Sama. This chapter proposes using <a href="/wiki/Quality_of_life" title="Quality of life">quality of life</a> measurements (a broader range of variables that life evaluation) in lieu of or in addition to overall life evaluations in future World Happiness Reports.
</p><p>Chapter 2, <i>Human Flourishing, the Common Good, and Catholic Social Teaching</i> is written by Anthony Annett. This chapter contains explanations for three theories: (1) It is human nature to broadly define happiness and understand the connection between happiness and the <a href="/wiki/Common_good" title="Common good">common good</a>, (2) that the current understanding of individuality is stripped of ties to the common good, and (3) that there is a need to restore the common good as central value for society. The chapter also proposes <a href="/wiki/Catholic_Church" title="Catholic Church">Catholic</a> school teachings as a model for restoring the common good as a dominant value.
</p><p>Chapter 3, <i>The Challenges of Public Happiness: An Historical-Methodological Reconstruction</i> is written by Luigino Bruni and Stefano Zemagni. This chapter contemplates Aristotelian concepts of happiness and virtue as they pertain to and support the findings in the World Happiness Reports regarding the impact of social support, trust in government, and equality of happiness.
</p><p>Chapter 4, The <i>Geography of Parenthood and Well-Being. Do Children Make Us Happy, Where and Why</i>? is written by Luca Stanca.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> This chapter examines other research findings that children do not add happiness to parents. Using data from the <a href="/wiki/World_Values_Survey" title="World Values Survey">World Values Survey</a>, it finds that, with the exception of widowed parents, having children has a negative effect on life satisfaction for parents in 2/3 of the 105 countries studied, with parents in richer countries suffering more. Once parents are <a href="/wiki/Old_age" title="Old age">old</a>, life satisfaction increases. The chapter concludes that "existing evidence is not conclusive" and a statement that the causes for the low life satisfaction levels may be that for richer countries, having children is valued less, and in poorer countries, people suffer in financial and time costs when they have children.
</p><p>Chapter 5, <i>Multidimensional Well-Being in Contemporary Europe: Analysis of the Use of Self-Organizing Map Allied to SHARE Data</i> is written by Mario Lucchini, Luca Crivelli<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> and Sara della Bella. This chapter contains a study of well-being data from older European adults. It finds that this chapter's study results were consistent with the World Happiness Report 2016 update: positive affect (feelings) have a stronger impact on a person's satisfaction with life than do negative affect (feelings).
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2015_World_Happiness_Report">2015 World Happiness Report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: 2015 World Happiness Report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<tbody><tr>
<th style="background: #F0F2F5; font-size:87%; padding:0.2em 0.3em; text-align:center;"><div style="display:inline;font-size:115%">Descriptions</div>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td style="border: solid 1px Silver; padding: 0.6em; background: White;">
<p>The 2015 World Happiness Report has eight chapters: (1) <i>Setting the Stage</i>, (2) <i>The Geography of World Happiness</i>, (3) <i>How Does Subjective Well-being Vary Around the World by Gender and Age?</i>, (4) <i>How to Make Policy When Happiness is the Goal</i>, (5) <i>Neuroscience of Happiness</i>, (6) <i>Healthy Young Minds Transforming the Mental Health of Children,</i> (7) <i>Human Values, Civil Economy, and Subjective Well-being</i>, and (8) <i>Investing in Social Capital.</i>
</p><p>Chapter 1, <i>Setting the Stage</i> is written by John F. Helliwell, Richard Layard and Jeffrey Sachs. This chapter celebrates the success of the happiness movement ("Happiness is increasingly considered a proper means of social progress and public policy."), citing the OECD Guidelines on Measuring Subjective Well-being, a referendum in the EU requiring member nations to measure happiness, and the success of the World Happiness reports (with readership at about 1.5 million), and the adoption of happiness by the government of the <a href="/wiki/United_Arab_Emirates" title="United Arab Emirates">United Arab Emirates</a>, and other areas. It sets an aspiration of the inclusion of subjective well-being into the 2015 Sustainable Development Goals (not fulfilled), and outlines the 2015 report. It also address the use of the term Happiness, identifying the cons (narrowness of the term, breath of the term, flakiness), and defining the use of the term for the reasons that the 2011 UN General Assembly Resolution 65/309 Happiness Towards A Holistic Approach to Development<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> and April 2012 UN High Level Meeting: Well-being and Happiness: Defining a New Economic Paradigm,<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> Bhutan's Gross National Happiness<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> philosophy, the term's "convening and attention attracting power", and the asset in a "double usage of happiness" as an emotional report and life evaluation.
</p><p>Chapter 2, <i>The Geography of Happiness</i> is written by John F. Helliwell, Hailing Huang and Shun Wang. This chapter reports the happiness of nations measured by life evaluations. It includes color coded maps and an analysis of six factors the account for the differences: (1) social support in terms of someone to count on in times of need, (2) GDP per capita (income), (3) life expectancy (in terms of healthy years), (4) sense of corruption in government and business (trust), (5) perceived freedom to make life decisions, and (6) generosity. The first three factors were found to have the biggest impact on a population's happiness. Crisis (<a href="/wiki/Natural_disaster" title="Natural disaster">natural disasters</a> and economic crisis) the quality of governance, and social support were found to be the key drivers for changes in national happiness levels, with the happiness of nations undergoing a crisis in which people have a strong sense of social support falling less than nations where people do not have a strong sense of social support.
</p><p>Chapter 3, <i>How Does Subjective Well-being Vary Around the Globe by Gender and Age?</i> is written by Nicole Fortin, John F. Helliwell and Shun Wang. This chapter uses data for 12 experiences: happiness (the emotion), smiling or laughing, enjoyment, feeling safe at night, feeling well rested, and feeling interested, as well as anger, worry, sadness, depression, stress and pain to examine differences by gender and age. Findings reported include that there is not a lot of difference in life evaluations between men and women across nations or within ages in a nation (women have slightly higher life evaluations than men: 0.09 on a ten-point scale). It reports that overall happiness falls into a U shape with age on the x axis and happiness on the y, with the low point being middle age (45-50) for most nations (in some happiness does not go up much in later life, so the shape is more of a downhill slide), and that the U shape holds for feeling well rested in all regions. If finds that that men generally feel safer at night than women but, when comparing countries, people in <a href="/wiki/Latin_America" title="Latin America">Latin America</a> have the lowest sense of safety at night, while people in <a href="/wiki/East_Asia" title="East Asia">East Asia</a> and <a href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western Europe">Western Europe</a> have the highest sense of safety at night. It also finds that as women age their sense of happiness declines and stress increases but worry decreases, as all people age their laughter, enjoyment and finding something of interest also declines, that anger is felt everywhere almost equally by men and women, stress peaks in the Middle Ages, and women experience depression more than men. It finds that where older people are happier, there is a sense of social support, freedom to make life choices and generosity (and income does not factor in as heavily as these three factors).
</p><p>Chapter 4, <i>How to Make Policy When Happiness is the Goal</i> is written by Richard Layard and <a href="/wiki/Gus_O%27Donnell" title="Gus O&#39;Donnell">Gus O'Donnell</a>. This chapter advocates for a "new form of cost-benefit analysis" for government expenditures in which a "critical level of extra happiness" yielded by a project is established. It contemplates the prioritization of increasing happiness of the happy vs. reducing misery of the miserable, as well as the issues of <a href="/wiki/Social_discount_rate" title="Social discount rate">discount rate</a> (weight) for the happiness of future generations. It includes a technical annex with equations for calculating the maximization for happiness in <a href="/wiki/Public_expenditure" title="Public expenditure">public expenditure</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tax_policy" title="Tax policy">tax policy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Regulation" title="Regulation">regulations</a>, the distribution of happiness and a discount rate.
</p><p>Chapter 5, <i>Neuroscience of Happiness</i> is written by Richard J. Dawson and Brianna S. Schuyler. This chapter reports on research in <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_science" title="Cognitive science">brain science</a> and happiness, identifying four aspects that account for happiness: (1) sustained positive emotion, (2) recovery of negative emotion (resilience), (3) <a href="/wiki/Empathy" title="Empathy">empathy</a>, altruism and pro-social behavior, and (4) mindfulness (mind-wandering/affective sickness). It concludes that the <a href="/wiki/Neuroplasticity" title="Neuroplasticity">brain's elasticity</a> indicates that one can change one's sense of happiness and life satisfaction (separate but overlapping positive consequences) levels by experiencing and practicing mindfulness, kindness, and generosity; and calls for more research on these topics.
</p><p>Chapter 6<i>, Healthy Young Minds: Transforming the <a href="/wiki/Mental_health" title="Mental health">Mental Health</a> of Children</i> is written by Richard Layard and Ann Hagell.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> This chapter identifies emotional development as of primary importance, (compared to academic and behavioral factors) in a <a href="/wiki/Child_development" title="Child development">child's development</a> and determination of whether a child will be a happy and well-functioning adult. It then focuses on the issue of <a href="/wiki/Mental_disorder" title="Mental disorder">mental illness</a> in children, citing the statistic that while worldwide 10% of the world's children (approximately 200 million) suffer from diagnosable mental health problems, even in the richest nations, only one quarter of these children of them are in treatment. It identifies the action steps to treating children with mental health problems: local community-lead child well-being programs, training health care professions to identify mental health problems in children, parity of esteem for mental and physical problems and treatment, access to <a href="/wiki/Evidence-based_medicine" title="Evidence-based medicine">evidence-based</a> mental health treatment for families and children, promotion of well-being in schools with well-being <a href="/wiki/Code_of_conduct" title="Code of conduct">codes</a> that inform the <a href="/wiki/Organizational_behavior" title="Organizational behavior">organizational behavior</a> of schools, training teachers to identify mental health in children, teachings of life skills, measuring of children's well-being by schools, development of free apps available internationally to treat mental illness in teens, and inclusion of mental health with the goal of physical health in the Sustainable Development goals. The chapter lists the benefits of treating children's mental health: improved educational performance, reduction in <a href="/wiki/Juvenile_delinquency" title="Juvenile delinquency">youth crimes</a>, improved earnings and employment in adulthood, and better <a href="/wiki/Parenting" title="Parenting">parenting</a> of the next generation.
</p><p>Chapter 7, <i>Human Values, Civil Economy and Subjective Well-being</i> is written by Leonardo Bechhetti,<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Luigino Bruni and Stefano Zamagni. This chapter begins with a critique of the field of economics ("Economics today looks like physics before the discovery of electrons"), identifying reductionism in which humans are conceived of as 100% self-interested individuals (economic reductionism), <a href="/wiki/Profit_maximization" title="Profit maximization">profit maximization</a> is prioritized over all other interests (corporate reductionism), and societal values are narrowly identified with GDP and ignore environmental, <a href="/wiki/Culture" title="Culture">cultural</a>, <a href="/wiki/Spirituality" title="Spirituality">spiritual</a> and relational aspects (value reductionism). The chapter them focuses on a theoretical approach termed "Civil Economy paradigm", and research about it demonstrating that going beyond reductionism leads to greater socialization for people and communities, and a rise in priority of the values of reciprocity, friendship, trustworthiness, and benevolence. It makes the argument that positive social relationships (trust, benevolence, shared <a href="/wiki/Identity_(social_science)" title="Identity (social science)">social identities</a>) yield happiness and positive economic outcomes. It ends with recommendations for move from the dominant model of elite-competitive democracy to a participatory/<a href="/wiki/Participation_(decision_making)" class="mw-redirect" title="Participation (decision making)">deliberative model</a> of democracy with bottom-up political and economic participation and incentives for non-selfish actions (<a href="/wiki/Altruism" title="Altruism">altruistic</a> people) and corporations with wider goals than pure profit (ethical and environmentally <a href="/wiki/Corporate_social_responsibility" title="Corporate social responsibility">responsible corporations</a>).
</p><p>Chapter 8, <i>Investing in Social Capital</i> is written by Jeffrey Sachs. This chapter focuses on "pro-sociality" ("individuals making decisions for the common good that may conflict with short-run <a href="/wiki/Egoism" title="Egoism">egoistic</a> incentives"). It identifies pro-social behaviors: honesty, benevolence, cooperation and trustworthiness. It recommends investment in <a href="/wiki/Social_capital" title="Social capital">social capital</a> through education, moral instruction, professional <a href="/wiki/Code_of_conduct" title="Code of conduct">codes of conduct</a>, public censure and condemnation of violators of public trust, and public policies to narrow income inequalities for countries where there is generalized distrust of government and business, pervasive <a href="/wiki/Corruption" title="Corruption">corruption</a> and lawless behavior (such as <a href="/wiki/Tax_evasion" title="Tax evasion">tax evasion</a>).
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<p><br />
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2013_World_Happiness_Report">2013 World Happiness Report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: 2013 World Happiness Report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<tbody><tr>
<th style="background: #F0F2F5; font-size:87%; padding:0.2em 0.3em; text-align:center;"><div style="display:inline;font-size:115%">Descriptions</div>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td style="border: solid 1px Silver; padding: 0.6em; background: White;">
<p>The 2013 World Happiness Report has eight chapters: (1) <i>Introduction</i>, (2) <i>World Happiness: Trends, Explanations and Distribution</i>, (3) <i>Mental Illness and Unhappiness</i>, (4) <i>The Objective Benefits of Subjective Well-being</i>, (5) <i>Restoring Virtue Ethics in the Quest for Happiness</i>, (6) <i>Using Well-being as a Guide to Policy</i>, (7) <i>The OECD Approach to Measuring Subjective Well-being</i>, and (8) <i>From Capabilities to Contentment: Testing the Links between Human Development and Life Satisfactio</i>n.
</p><p>Chapter 1, <i>Introduction</i> is written by John F. Helliwell, Richard Layard and Jeffrey Sachs. It synopsizes the chapters and gives a discussion of the term <i>happiness</i>.
</p><p>Chapter 2, <i>World Happiness: Trends, Explanations and <a href="/wiki/Distribution_(mathematics)" title="Distribution (mathematics)">Distributions</a></i> is written by John F. Helliwell and Shun Wang. It provides ratings among countries and regions for satisfaction with life using the Cantril Ladder, positive and negative affect (emotions), and <a href="/wiki/Logarithm" title="Logarithm">log</a> of GDP per capita, years of healthy life expectancy, having someone to count on in times of trouble, perceptions of <a href="/wiki/Corruption" title="Corruption">corruption</a>, prevalence of <a href="/wiki/Generosity" title="Generosity">generosity</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Liberty" title="Liberty">freedom</a> to make life choices.
</p><p>Chapter 3, <i>Mental Illness and Unhappines</i>s is written by Richard Layard, Dan Chisholm, Vikram Patel, and Shekhar Saxel. It identifies the far ranging prevalence of <a href="/wiki/Mental_disorder" title="Mental disorder">mental illness</a> around the world (10% of the world's population at one time) and provides the evidence showing that "mental illness is a highly influential - and...the single biggest - determinant of misery". It concludes with examples of interventions implemented by countries around the world.
</p><p>Chapter 4, <i>The Objective Benefits of Subjective Well-being</i> is written by Jan-Emmanuel de Neve, Ed Diener, Louis Tay and Cody Xuereb. It provides an explanation of the benefits of subjective well-being (happiness) on health &amp; longevity, income, <a href="/wiki/Productivity" title="Productivity">productivity</a> &amp; <a href="/wiki/Organizational_behavior" title="Organizational behavior">organizational behavior</a>, and individual &amp; social behavior. It touches on the role of happiness in <a href="/wiki/Human_evolution" title="Human evolution">human evolution</a> through rewarding behaviors that increase evolutionary success and beneficial to survival.
</p><p>Chapter 5, <i>Restoring Virtue Ethics in the Quest for Happiness</i> is written by Jeffrey Sachs. It argues that "a renewed focus on the role of ethics, and in particular of virtuous behavior, in happiness could lead us to new and effective <a href="/wiki/Strategy" title="Strategy">strategies</a> for raising individual, national and global well-being", looking to the <a href="/wiki/Noble_Eightfold_Path" title="Noble Eightfold Path">eightfold noble path</a> (the teachings of the <a href="/wiki/Dharma" title="Dharma">dharma</a> handed down in the <a href="/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">Buddhist</a> tradition that encompass wise view/understanding, wise intention, wise speech, wise action, wise livelihood, and effort, concentration and mindfulness), <a href="/wiki/Aristotelianism" title="Aristotelianism">Aristotelian philosophy</a> (people are social animals, "with individual happiness secured only within a political community...[which] should organize its institutions to promote virtuous behavior), and Christian doctrine of <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Aquinas" title="Thomas Aquinas">St. Thomas Aquinas</a> ("placing happiness in the context of servicing God's will"). It gives an explanation of the evolution of the field of economics up t the "failures of hyper-commercialism" and suggests an antidote based on four global ethical values: (1) non-violence and respect for life, (2) justice and solidarity, (3) honesty and tolerance, and (4) mutual esteem and partnership.
</p><p>Chapter 6, <i>Using Well-being as Guide to Public Policy</i> is written by <a href="/wiki/Gus_O%27Donnell" title="Gus O&#39;Donnell">Gus O'Donnell</a>. This chapter gives a status report on the issues governments grapple with in adopting well-being and happiness measures and goals for policy, from understanding the data or establishing whether a specific policy improves well-being, to figuring out how to "incorporate well-being into standard policy making". It provides examples of efforts to measure happiness and well-being from Bhutan, New Zealand, South Africa, the UK, and cities and communities in the US, Canada, Australia and Tasmania. It identifies the key policy areas of health, transport and education for policy makers to focus on and includes discussions about interpersonal comparability (concentrating on "getting people out of misery" instead of making happy people happier), discount rate (do we invest more in happiness for people today or in the future?) and putting a monetary value on happiness for policy trade off decisions (e.g. If "a 10% reduction in noise increase SWB by one unit, then we can infer that a 10% reduction is "worth" $1,000" when $1,000 would increase a person's SWB by one unit).
</p><p>Chapter 7, <i>The OECD Approach to Measuring Subjective Well-being</i> is written by Martine Durand and Conal Smith. This chapter was written the same year the OECD issued its Guidelines on Measuring Subjective Well-being,<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> and is a synopsis of such. It includes a definition for subjective well-being: life evaluation (a person's reflection on their life and life circumstances), affect (positive and negative emotions) and <a href="/wiki/Eudaimonia" title="Eudaimonia">eudaimonia</a>; core measures, a discussion on <a href="/wiki/Data_collection" title="Data collection">data collection</a> processes, <a href="/wiki/Survey_methodology" title="Survey methodology">survey</a> and sample design, other aspects of using subjective well-being metrics, and ideas on how policy-makers can use subjective well-being data. It surveys the status of wealthy countries subjective well-being data collection process, and identifies future directions of experimentation and better income measures, citing the <a href="/wiki/Easterlin_paradox" title="Easterlin paradox">Easterlin Paradox</a> as the basis for this call.
</p><p>Chapter 8, <i>From Capabilities to Contentment: Testing the Links between Human Development and Life Satisfaction</i> is written by Jon Hall.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> This chapter explains the components of human development using objective metrics: (1) education, health and command over income and nutrition resources, (2) participation and freedom, (3) human security, (4) equity, and (5) <a href="/wiki/Sustainability" title="Sustainability">sustainability</a>; key findings of the <a href="/wiki/Human_Development_Index" title="Human Development Index">Human Development Index</a> (HDI) ("weak relationship between economic growth and changes in health and education" as well as life expectancy), and examines the relationship between the HDI and happiness, finding that (1) components of the HDI "correlate strongly with better life evaluations", and (2) there is a strong relationship between life evaluation and the "non-income HDI". It contemplates measurement of conditions of life beyond the HDI that are important to well-being: (1) better working conditions, (2) security against crime and physical violence, (3) participation in economic and political activities, (4) freedom and (5) inequality. The concludes with the statements that the HDI and SWB have similar approaches and importantly connected, with the two disciplines offering alternative and complementary views of development.
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2012_World_Happiness_Report">2012 World Happiness Report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: 2012 World Happiness Report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<tbody><tr>
<th style="background: #F0F2F5; font-size:87%; padding:0.2em 0.3em; text-align:center;"><div style="display:inline;font-size:115%">Descriptions</div>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td style="border: solid 1px Silver; padding: 0.6em; background: White;">
<p>The 2012 World Happiness Report was issued at the UN High Level Meeting Well-being and Happiness: Defining a New Economic Paradigm<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> by editors <a href="/wiki/John_F._Helliwell" title="John F. Helliwell">John F. Helliwell</a>, <a href="/wiki/Richard_Layard,_Baron_Layard" title="Richard Layard, Baron Layard">Richard Layard</a> and <a href="/wiki/Jeffrey_Sachs" title="Jeffrey Sachs">Jeffrey Sachs</a>. Part one has an introduction (chapter 1) and three chapters: (2) <i>the State of World Happiness</i>, (3) <i>Causes of Happiness and Misery, Some Policy Implications.</i> Part two has three chapters, each a case study, of Bhutan, the United Kingdom Office of National Statistics, and the <a href="/wiki/OECD" title="OECD">OECD</a>.
</p><p>Chapter 1, <i>The Introduction</i> is by Jeffrey Sachs and references <a href="/wiki/Gautama_Buddha" title="Gautama Buddha">Buddha</a> and <a href="/wiki/Aristotle" title="Aristotle">Aristotle</a>, identifies today's era as the <a href="/wiki/Anthropocene" title="Anthropocene">anthropocene</a>, and identifies the reasons <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">GDP</a> is not a sufficient measure to guide governments and <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">society</a>.
</p><p>Chapter 2, <i>The</i> <i>State of World Happiness,</i> is written by <a href="/wiki/John_F._Helliwell" title="John F. Helliwell">John F. Helliwell</a> and Shun Wang,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> and contains a discussion of <a href="/wiki/Tripartite_model_of_subjective_well-being" class="mw-redirect" title="Tripartite model of subjective well-being">subjective well-being</a> measures that ranges from the validity of subjective well-being measures to the seriousness of happiness, happiness set points and cultural comparisons, and it includes data from the <a href="/wiki/Gallup_(company)" title="Gallup (company)">Gallup</a> World Poll, <a href="/wiki/European_Social_Survey" title="European Social Survey">European Social Survey</a>, and the World Values Survey.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Chapter 3, <i>The Causes of Happiness and Misery</i> is written by <a href="/wiki/Richard_Layard,_Baron_Layard" title="Richard Layard, Baron Layard">Richard Layard</a>, Andrew Clark,<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> and Claudia Senik,<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> and contemplates research on the impact on happiness of the external factors of <a href="/wiki/Income" title="Income">income</a>, work, <a href="/wiki/Community" title="Community">community</a> and governance, <a href="/wiki/Value_(ethics)" title="Value (ethics)">values</a> and <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religion</a>, as well as the internal factors of <a href="/wiki/Mental_health" title="Mental health">mental health</a>, <a href="/wiki/Health" title="Health">physical health</a>, family experience, <a href="/wiki/Education" title="Education">education</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Gender" title="Gender">gender</a> and age.
</p><p>Chapter 4, <i>Some <a href="/wiki/Policy" title="Policy">Policy</a> Implications,</i> written by John F. Helliwell, Richard Layard and Jeffrey Sachs, calls for a greater understanding on how governments can measure happiness, the determinants of happiness, and use of happiness data and findings about determinants for policy purposes. It also highlights the role of <a href="/wiki/Gross_domestic_product" title="Gross domestic product">GDP</a> ("GDP is important but not all that is important") as a guide to policy makers, the importance that policy makers should place on providing opportunities for employment; the role of happiness in policy making ("Making happiness an objective of governments would not therefore lead to the "servile society", and indeed quite the contrary...Happiness comes from an opportunity to mold one's own future, and thus depends on a robust level of freedom."); the role of values and religion ("In well-functioning societies there is widespread support for the <a href="/wiki/Universal_value" title="Universal value">universal value</a> that we should treat others as we would like them to treat us. We need to cultivate <a href="/wiki/Norm_(social)" class="mw-redirect" title="Norm (social)">social norms</a> so that the rich and powerful are never given a feeling of impunity vis-à-vis the rest of society."); calls for wider access to psychological therapies in a section on <a href="/wiki/Mental_health" title="Mental health">mental health</a> citing the fact that one third of all families are affected by mental illness; identifies improvements in physical health as "probably the single most important factor that has improved human happiness" and calls out the <a href="/wiki/Economic_inequality" title="Economic inequality">rich-poor gap</a> in health care between rich and poor countries; calls on workplace and governmental policies that encourage <a href="/wiki/Work%E2%80%93life_balance" title="Work–life balance">work-life balance</a> and reduce stress, including family support and <a href="/wiki/Child_care" title="Child care">child care</a>; and states that "<a href="/wiki/Universal_access_to_education" title="Universal access to education">Universal access to education</a> is widely judged to be a basic <a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human rights">human right</a>..." The chapter concludes with a <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophical</a> discussion.
</p><p>Chapter 5, <i>Case Study: <a href="/wiki/Bhutan" title="Bhutan">Bhutan</a> Gross National Happiness and the GNH Index</i> is written by Karma Ura,<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> Sabine Alkire,<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> and Tsoki Zangmo. It gives a short history of the development of the Gross National Happiness (GNH) concept in Bhutan, and an explanation of the GNH index, <a href="/wiki/Data_collection" title="Data collection">data collection</a> and <a href="/wiki/Data_analysis" title="Data analysis">data analysis</a> process, including the rating <a href="/wiki/Methodology" title="Methodology">methodology</a> to determine if an individual experiences happiness sufficiency levels, as well as the policy and lifestyle implications
</p><p>Chapter 6, <i>Case Study: ONS Measuring Subjective Well-being: The UK Office of National Statistics Experience</i> is written by Stephen Hicks. It covers the basis for the creation of the Measuring National Well-being Programme<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> in the UK's Office of National Statistics<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> (ONS), and the development of their methodology for measuring well-being.
</p><p>Chapter 5, <i>Case Study OECD Guidelines on Measuring Subjective Well-being</i> is an explanation about the process and rationale the OECD was undertaking to develop its Guidelines on Measuring Subjective Well-being,<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> which it issued in 2013.
</p>
</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="International_rankings">International rankings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: International rankings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Data is collected from people in over 150 countries. Each variable measured reveals a populated-weighted average score on a scale running from 0 to 10 that is tracked over time and compared against other countries. These variables currently include: real <a href="/wiki/GDP_per_capita" class="mw-redirect" title="GDP per capita">GDP per capita</a>, social support, healthy <a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy" title="Life expectancy">life expectancy</a>, freedom to make life choices, generosity, and perceptions of corruption. Each country is also compared against a hypothetical nation called <a href="/wiki/Dystopia" title="Dystopia">Dystopia</a>. Dystopia represents the lowest national averages for each key variable and is, along with residual error, used as a regression benchmark.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2019_report">2019 report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: 2019 report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The 2019 report features the happiness score averaged over the years 2016–2018. As per the 2019 Happiness Index, <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> is the happiest country in the world. <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iceland" title="Iceland">Iceland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">Netherlands</a> hold the next top positions. The report was published on 20 March 2019 by UN. The full report can be read at <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://worldhappiness.report/ed/2019/">2019 Report</a>. The World Happiness Report is a landmark survey of the state of global happiness.
</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2018_report">2018 report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: 2018 report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The 2018 report features the happiness score averaged over the years 2015–2017. As per the 2018 Happiness Index, <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a> is the happiest country in the world. <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a>, <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iceland" title="Iceland">Iceland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a> hold the next top positions. The report was published on 14 March 2018 by UN. The full report can be read at <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://worldhappiness.report/ed/2018/">2018 Report</a>. The World Happiness Report is a landmark survey of the state of global happiness. The World Happiness Report 2018, which ranks 156 countries by their happiness levels, and 117 countries by the happiness of their immigrants, was released on March 14 at a launch event at the Pontifical Academy of Sciences in the Vatican.
</p>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2017_report">2017 report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: 2017 report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://worldhappiness.report/ed/2017/">2017 report</a> features the happiness score averaged over the years 2014–2016. For that timespan, Norway was the overall happiest country in the world, even though oil prices had dropped. Close behind were Denmark, Iceland and Switzerland in a tight pack. Four of the top five countries follow the <a href="/wiki/Nordic_model" title="Nordic model">Nordic model</a>. All the top ten countries had high scores in the six categories. The ranked follow-on countries in the top ten are: Finland, the Netherlands, Canada, New Zealand, Australia, and Sweden.
</p>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2016_report">2016 report</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: 2016 report">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div style="margin-left:0">
<table class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" style="background: transparent; text-align: left; border: 1px solid Silver; margin: 0.2em auto auto; width:100%; clear: both; padding: 1px;">

<tbody><tr>
<th style="background: #F0F2F5; font-size:87%; padding:0.2em 0.3em; text-align:center;"><div style="display:inline;font-size:115%">Table</div>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td style="border: solid 1px Silver; padding: 0.6em; background: White;">
<p>Legend:<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="width:100%; background:none;">

<tbody><tr>
<td valign="top">
<div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color: #E4D00A; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Explained by: GDP per capita</div>
<div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color: #C23B22; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Explained by: Social support</div>
<div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color: #08457E; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Explained by: Healthy life expectancy</div>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<div class="legend" style="-webkit-column-break-inside: avoid;page-break-inside: avoid;break-inside: avoid-column"><span class="legend-color" style="display:inline-block; width:1.5em; height:1.5em; margin:1px 0; border:1px solid black; background-color: #A4C639; color:black; font-size:100%; text-align:center;">&#160;</span>&#160;Explained by: Freedom to make life choices</div>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Criticism">Criticism</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Criticism">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Metrics">Metrics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Metrics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Some argue that questioning on overall life status leads humans to overweigh income concerns, rather than <a href="/wiki/Happiness" title="Happiness">happiness</a>. For instance <a href="/wiki/Colombia" title="Colombia">Colombia</a> came 37th in the 2018 <a href="/wiki/World_Happiness_Index" class="mw-redirect" title="World Happiness Index">World Happiness Index</a> but 1st by daily emotional experience.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> In 2012 "A Gallup survey on happiest countries had a completely different list [compared with the World Happiness Index], with Panama first, followed by Paraguay, El Salvador, and Venezuela". Similarly a Pew survey of 43 countries in 2014 (which excluded most of Europe) had Mexico, Israel and Venezuela finishing first, second and third.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Others point out that the ranking results are counterintuitive when it come to some dimensions, for "instance if rate of suicide is used as a metric for measuring unhappiness, (the opposite of happiness), then some of the countries which are ranked among the top 20 happiest countries in the world will also feature among the top 20 with the highest suicide rates in the world."<sup id="cite_ref-dailytrust.com.ng_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dailytrust.com.ng-48">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Methodology">Methodology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Methodology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>From an econometric perspective, some statisticians argue the statistical methodology mentioned in the first world happiness report using 9 domains is unreliable.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Others argue that the World Happiness Report model uses a limited subset of indicators used by other models and does not use an Index function like peer econometric models such as <a href="/wiki/Gross_National_Well-being" title="Gross National Well-being">Gross National Well-being</a> Index 2005, Sustainable Society Index of 2008,<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> OECD <a href="/wiki/Better_Life_Index" class="mw-redirect" title="Better Life Index">Better Life Index</a> of 2011, and Bhutan <a href="/wiki/Gross_National_Happiness" title="Gross National Happiness">Gross National Happiness</a> Index of 2012, and <a href="/wiki/Social_Progress_Index" title="Social Progress Index">Social Progress Index</a> of 2013.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Philosophical_concerns">Philosophical concerns</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Philosophical concerns">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>From a philosophical perspective, critics argue that measuring the happiness of a group of people is misleading because happiness is an individual matter. They state "[for] the Dalai Lama, Gandhi, Tolstoy and several others, happiness is an individual choice that is independent of the society, its structures and enabling or dis-enabling conditions and not something to be measured using variables that can only capture a nation's well-being. This means therefore that one cannot really talk of a happy or unhappy nation, but of happy or unhappy individuals."<sup id="cite_ref-dailytrust.com.ng_48-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dailytrust.com.ng-48">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">

</li>
<li id="cite_note-World-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-World_39-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Score not included in the original report, but was attained by adding up all the scores and then dividing for an average: 5.3053935483871.</span>

<li id="cite_note-KOS-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-KOS_44-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Kosovo is the subject of a territorial dispute between the <a href="/wiki/Kosovo" title="Kosovo">Republic of Kosovo</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Serbia" title="Serbia">Republic of Serbia</a>. The Republic of Kosovo <a href="/wiki/2008_Kosovo_declaration_of_independence" title="2008 Kosovo declaration of independence">unilaterally declared independence</a> on 17 February 2008, but <a href="/wiki/Kosovo%E2%80%93Serbia_relations" title="Kosovo–Serbia relations">Serbia continues to claim</a> it as part of its <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_Province_of_Kosovo_and_Metohija" title="Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija">own sovereign territory</a>. The two governments <a href="/wiki/Belgrade%E2%80%93Pristina_negotiations" title="Belgrade–Pristina negotiations">began to normalise relations</a> in 2013, as part of the <a href="/wiki/Brussels_Agreement_(2013)" title="Brussels Agreement (2013)">2013 Brussels Agreement</a>. Kosovo is currently recognized as an independent state by 97 out of the 193 <a href="/wiki/Member_states_of_the_United_Nations" title="Member states of the United Nations">United Nations member states</a>. In total, <a href="/wiki/International_recognition_of_Kosovo" title="International recognition of Kosovo">112</a> UN member states recognized Kosovo at some point, of which 15 later withdrew their recognition.</span>
</li>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="External_links">External links</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=World_Happiness_Report&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul><li><span class="official-website"><span class="url"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://s3.amazonaws.com/happiness-report/2020/WHR20.pdf">Official website</a></span></span></li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://unsdsn.org/">Sustainable Development Solutions Network</a></li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/20/norway-ousts-denmark-as-worlds-happiest-country-un-report/">The Guardian</a></li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://i.redd.it/7td6kwossi801.jpg">Map of changes of happiness index points in Europe between 2005 and 2016</a></li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.statsilk.com/maps/world-happiness-report-interactive-map">Interactive map of countries by happiness score as well as GDP, life expectancy, generosity, social support, freedom, and corruption</a></li></ul>
<div role="navigation" class="navbox" aria-labelledby="Lists_of_countries_by_quality_of_life_rankings" style="padding:3px"><table class="nowraplinks hlist mw-collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner" style="border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit"><tbody><tr><th scope="col" class="navbox-title" colspan="2"><div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Quality_of_life_country_lists" title="Template:Quality of life country lists"><abbr title="View this template" style=";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Quality_of_life_country_lists" title="Template talk:Quality of life country lists"><abbr title="Discuss this template" style=";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Quality_of_life_country_lists&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template" style=";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div><div id="Lists_of_countries_by_quality_of_life_rankings" style="font-size:114%;margin:0 4em"><a href="/wiki/Lists_of_countries_and_territories" title="Lists of countries and territories">Lists of countries</a> by <a href="/wiki/Quality_of_life" title="Quality of life">quality of life</a> <a href="/wiki/List_of_international_rankings" title="List of international rankings">rankings</a></div></th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="navbox-group" style="width:1%">General</th><td class="navbox-list navbox-odd" style="text-align:left;border-left-width:2px;border-left-style:solid;width:100%;padding:0px"><div style="padding:0em 0.25em">
